==References in popular culture==

The ballad has inspired a very large number of reworkings in popular culture.

Most famously, a translation of a Danish variant ([[Danmarks gamle Folkeviser|DFG 47B]], from Peter Syv's 1695 edition) into German by [[Johann Gottfried Herder]] as "Erlkönigs tochter" inspired [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe|Johann Wolfgang von Goethe's]] poem "[[Der Erlkönig]]", which developed the concept of the [[Erlking]].

The ballad was one of the inspirations for the 1828 play ''[[Elves' Hill]]'' by [[Johan Ludvig Heiberg (poet)|Johan Ludvig Heiberg]].

Other works inspired by "Elveskud" include [[Henrik Ibsen]]'s 1856 play ''[[Olaf Liljekrans]]''; [[Kristín Marja Baldursdóttir]]'s 1995 novel ''[[The Seagull's Laughter|Mávahlátur]]''; and [[Böðvar Guðmundsson|Böðvar Guðmundsson's]] 2012 novel ''[[Töfrahöllin]]''.

